00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:42.420
for the sprint.

00:12:42.420 --> 00:12:43.920
KAI HALEY: So it
sounds like there's

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:45.570
a lot of work that
goes into this,

00:12:45.570 --> 00:12:48.660
and you have to start planning
pretty far in advance.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:54.720
Is there a particularly good
time to sprint, or a time

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:57.090
when you absolutely
don't want to sprint?

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:00.540
SUMIER PHALAKE: Yeah, so there's
a couple of really good moments

00:13:00.540 --> 00:13:02.600
in the product life
cycle when it's actually

00:13:02.600 --> 00:13:04.950
really good to run a sprint.

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:07.530
So one of them is when
the product is really

00:13:07.530 --> 00:13:09.780
in its early stages.

00:13:09.780 --> 00:13:11.610
And it's just like
a kernel of an idea.

00:13:11.610 --> 00:13:13.590
You don't know
what it looks like.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:16.300
No one's really formed it
really well yet in their brain.

00:13:16.300 --> 00:13:18.960
So that's a great time
to bring a lot of people

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.060
together
cross-functionally and get

00:13:21.060 --> 00:13:22.740
a lot of experts in the room.

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:24.960
And then just kind of spend
a few days hashing it out

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:26.520
and coming out
with a good product

00:13:26.520 --> 00:13:29.907
strategy, a good vision,
maybe a couple of hypotheses

00:13:29.907 --> 00:13:30.990
that you want to test out.

00:13:30.990 --> 00:13:35.640
So I think that's a great
time to jump on a sprint.

00:13:35.640 --> 00:13:37.140
The other time is
actually later on,

00:13:37.140 --> 00:13:41.610
when your product is actually
launched, and you have data,

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:43.560
and some of it is
working really well.

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:45.040
And then maybe
parts of it are not.

00:13:45.040 --> 00:13:47.970
So for example, it's a shopping
site, and the check out flow

00:13:47.970 --> 00:13:49.200
is not working well.

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:50.530
You're losing users.

00:13:50.530 --> 00:13:54.720
So how do we fix this one
experience or this one journey?

00:13:54.720 --> 00:13:58.290
And that's actually a really
nice tactical contained problem

00:13:58.290 --> 00:14:00.090
to solve with a group of people.

00:14:00.090 --> 00:14:03.060
You can expect to have a
really nice solution by the end

00:14:03.060 --> 00:14:04.137
of four or five days.

00:14:04.137 --> 00:14:05.970
And you can actually
think laterally, right?

00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:08.670
Like as a group, you can
think of four or five

00:14:08.670 --> 00:14:10.490
different solutions,
and then diverge,

00:14:10.490 --> 00:14:13.300
and then converge on to the
ones that make the most sense.

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:16.560
So it really speeds
up the process

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:19.260
instead of doing this
regular waterfall model where

00:14:19.260 --> 00:14:20.877
you design something,
you test it out,

00:14:20.877 --> 00:14:22.460
then you go back to
the drawing board.

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:24.509
You actually do it
in parallel, and then

00:14:24.509 --> 00:14:25.800
you explore a bunch of options.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:27.330
And then at the end
of the week, you

00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:30.600
have a really good solution.

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:34.010
When not do sprint actually
is really interesting.

00:14:34.010 --> 00:14:36.160
So don't sprint when
you don't have time.

00:14:36.160 --> 00:14:41.590
And so if you've seen
the iceberg example, what

00:14:41.590 --> 00:14:44.500
you see on the day of the
sprint is actually just the tip

00:14:44.500 --> 00:14:46.130
of the iceberg, right?

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:48.330
All the planning that
happens to make the sprint

00:14:48.330 --> 00:14:52.080
a success, which is the majority
of the iceberg you can't see.

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:54.967
So it takes a while
to plan this thing

00:14:54.967 --> 00:14:56.050
and set it up for success.

00:14:56.050 --> 00:14:57.130
And if you don't have
the time to do it,

00:14:57.130 --> 00:14:58.921
if someone says I want
to sprint next week,

00:14:58.921 --> 00:15:02.540
just say no, it's
not going to happen.

00:15:02.540 --> 00:15:05.410
And then also don't do it when
your team doesn't have time.

00:15:05.410 --> 00:15:07.420
You're in the final
stages of launch,

00:15:07.420 --> 00:15:10.360
everyone's head's down, trying
to get something out the door.

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:12.760
That is absolutely the wrong
time to try to run a sprint,

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:14.920
because no one's in
the right mindset

00:15:14.920 --> 00:15:16.530
to go back to the drawing board.

00:15:16.530 --> 00:15:19.150
You'll get a lot of resistance.

00:15:19.150 --> 00:15:21.820
Make sure you get a
cross-functional team.

00:15:21.820 --> 00:15:23.520
You can do a sprint
with designers,

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:24.730
but what's the point?

00:15:24.730 --> 00:15:28.240
Because a lot of
it is about getting

00:15:28.240 --> 00:15:30.340
cross-functional
consensus and buy-in.

00:15:30.340 --> 00:15:31.930
You want people to
co-create and feel

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:34.030
like they have
ownership in the design.

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:35.680
And if you can't
do that, then you

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:39.020
lose something really valuable
from the sprint process.

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:41.920
And then lastly, I don't know if
you guys have experienced this,

00:15:41.920 --> 00:15:43.711
but sometimes you'll
have a stakeholder who

00:15:43.711 --> 00:15:45.550
has a solution in their brain.

00:15:45.550 --> 00:15:47.620
And they're like, I
want to run a sprint,

00:15:47.620 --> 00:15:51.430
because I want to validate that
what I have in mind is true.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.250
And that's also not a
good time to run a sprint,

00:15:54.250 --> 00:15:56.560
because sprints are
very, very bottom up,

00:15:56.560 --> 00:15:58.690
and you have to allow
the space for people

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:00.080
to come up with their own ideas.

00:16:00.080 --> 00:16:01.996
And sometimes they're
going to completely defy

00:16:01.996 --> 00:16:04.012
your expectations,
and that's OK.

00:16:04.012 --> 00:16:06.220
And if your stakeholders
are not all right with that,

00:16:06.220 --> 00:16:09.254
then you shouldn't run a sprint.

00:16:09.254 --> 00:16:11.420
RATNA DESAI: I think the
best time to run a sprint--

00:16:11.420 --> 00:16:13.250
and this is coming
from the perspective

00:16:13.250 --> 00:16:16.070
of working at Google,
which is a very, very

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:19.580
large organization with multiple
organizations within it--

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:21.800
is really when we
start annual planning.

00:16:21.800 --> 00:16:25.490
So our OKR process
is quite rigorous,

00:16:25.490 --> 00:16:28.920
and it's a good time to start
at the beginning of the year,

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:31.410
or I would even say at
the end of last year,

00:16:31.410 --> 00:16:33.650
the previous year, so
that you can really

00:16:33.650 --> 00:16:38.930
get runway on these ideas,
and then refine them quarter

00:16:38.930 --> 00:16:40.080
by quarter.

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:42.200
And so what this
allows is it allows

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:45.650
that kind of
cross-pollination of ideas

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:49.980
very early on in the planning
stage of the business strategy.

00:16:49.980 --> 00:16:52.160
And so it's key to
get there early.

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:55.280
The other point to make
about the best time

00:16:55.280 --> 00:16:58.280
is that it's really when the
right people are in the room

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:00.350
and are craving alignment.

00:17:00.350 --> 00:17:04.160
If there's no shared vision,
for example, for a product,

00:17:04.160 --> 00:17:07.550
and people are just kind of
stumbling and misinterpreting

00:17:07.550 --> 00:17:11.150
the goals, those things
are good symptoms

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:14.720
to pay attention to
in any organization,

00:17:14.720 --> 00:17:18.290
and to really then address it
with this wonderful methodology

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:20.839
that can stem anywhere from
a couple hours of getting

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:24.450
together and gaining that
alignment, or several days.

00:17:24.450 --> 00:17:27.079
And so this investment and
this customization can happen,

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:30.170
and that's what's really
lovely about this sprint method

00:17:30.170 --> 00:17:31.280
that we have.

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:33.500
And the wrong time is
when you really don't

00:17:33.500 --> 00:17:35.480
have the right
people in the room,

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:39.770
because it's ultimately going
to lead to a product idea that

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:41.990
isn't fully fleshed
out or doesn't

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:44.570
have the right stakeholder
investment upfront.

00:17:44.570 --> 00:17:48.620
So that kind of
upfront investment

00:17:48.620 --> 00:17:52.460
is so valuable down the road
when you're launching product.

00:17:52.460 --> 00:17:56.890
And it really saves teams
so much time in the end.

00:17:56.890 --> 00:17:58.640
JOSH LOVEJOY: Yeah,
you bring up the point

00:17:58.640 --> 00:18:02.390
about when teams are sort of
stuck in a product lifecycle.

00:18:02.390 --> 00:18:08.170
I've seen sprints unstick
teams so many times.

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:11.600
The test I like to
run is if someone

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:13.640
writes a doc about a
feature or a product,

00:18:13.640 --> 00:18:17.150
and then the email thread
that spawns out of that doc

00:18:17.150 --> 00:18:19.460
is longer than the
doc itself, it's

00:18:19.460 --> 00:18:21.950
probably a pretty good time
to get some people in a room

00:18:21.950 --> 00:18:23.584
and talk.

00:18:23.584 --> 00:18:25.250
You're frequently
dealing with this kind

00:18:25.250 --> 00:18:27.590
of cognitive dissonance
of like, well,

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:30.410
taking a bunch of people offline
and putting them in a room,

00:18:30.410 --> 00:18:33.070
and having them just talk to
each other for multiple days.

00:18:33.070 --> 00:18:34.820
That's like a ton of
investment, and we're

00:18:34.820 --> 00:18:36.680
going to lose all
sorts of productivity.

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:38.990
And the secret is
actually you gain

00:18:38.990 --> 00:18:41.150
like months of productivity.

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:44.330
If you get people from
different disciplines who

00:18:44.330 --> 00:18:46.790
have different perspectives
and different backgrounds who

00:18:46.790 --> 00:18:51.020
can come together and align, you
save so many different cycles

00:18:51.020 --> 00:18:53.266
of churn and back and forth.

00:18:53.266 --> 00:18:55.010
I even recently
we had a situation

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:57.050
where a product I
was involved with

00:18:57.050 --> 00:18:58.760
had some research
findings come back

00:18:58.760 --> 00:19:01.160
that were pretty surprising
and pretty at odds with some

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:03.110
of our core belief systems.

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:06.560
And we rallied together
a diverse set of folks

00:19:06.560 --> 00:19:09.920
for like three hours
and came up with--

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:11.690
just presented the
research, talked

00:19:11.690 --> 00:19:14.840
through a bunch of common
themes we were seeing,

00:19:14.840 --> 00:19:16.550
and by the end of
that session, we

00:19:16.550 --> 00:19:19.070
had product tenets that now
have taken us into a point where

00:19:19.070 --> 00:19:20.460
we're ready to launch.

00:19:20.460 --> 00:19:23.500
And that's just crazy
amounts of efficiency gain.

00:19:26.430 --> 00:19:29.610
KAI HALEY: You all mentioned
a cross-functional team

00:19:29.610 --> 00:19:33.750
and getting the right
people there in the room.

00:19:33.750 --> 00:19:36.990
Can you talk a little bit about
the most successful composition

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:39.060
of roles for a sprint?

00:19:39.060 --> 00:19:40.992
Sounds like that's
really important.

00:19:40.992 --> 00:19:41.700
RATNA DESAI: Yes.

00:19:41.700 --> 00:19:44.550
And I think it was touched
on earlier, is that I call it

00:19:44.550 --> 00:19:45.960
kind of the trifecta, right?

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:49.200
You need your
product manager, you

00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:52.890
need your [INAUDIBLE] partner,
and you need your UX person

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:53.670
in the room.

00:19:53.670 --> 00:19:56.280
Now that said, it's really
dependent on the challenge.

00:19:56.280 --> 00:19:59.880
Oftentimes, if we're solving
for a health care business

00:19:59.880 --> 00:20:01.269
challenge, I want a physician.

00:20:01.269 --> 00:20:03.060
And if I can't get a
physician in the room,

00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:06.510
I certainly want an interview
with a subject matter expert.

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:08.520
So there are these
ways in which we

00:20:08.520 --> 00:20:11.190
can augment the
core working team

00:20:11.190 --> 00:20:15.990
with stakeholder interviews,
subject matter, expertise.

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:19.290
And it really goes a long way,
because you're essentially

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:21.900
creating this real
microcosm of what

00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:25.920
we call a sprint team, which is
essentially practicing what it

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:30.180
means to be a growth org,
right, a constantly learning

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:32.340
and evolving organization.

00:20:32.340 --> 00:20:35.340
And we do these in these
little sprint pods,

00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:38.760
but essentially it can be
applied to the entire company.

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:40.920
Our technology is moving fast.

00:20:40.920 --> 00:20:45.420
We're all kind of moving a
million miles an hour in terms

00:20:45.420 --> 00:20:48.850
of what we're going to produce
and put out in the market.

00:20:48.850 --> 00:20:50.850
So it's really
our responsibility

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:53.520
to get that trifecta and
the right people in the room

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:57.330
because the audiences and the
global audiences we relate to

00:20:57.330 --> 00:21:02.370
with our end user is so diverse,
that really the onus is on each

00:21:02.370 --> 00:21:05.180
of us to make sure
that the seeds planted

00:21:05.180 --> 00:21:09.660
and the DNA of this idea
that will eventually become

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:11.940
a product living
in someone's life

00:21:11.940 --> 00:21:14.610
is a reflection of
society at large.

00:21:14.610 --> 00:21:17.220
And so you want those
kinds of cultural nuances,

00:21:17.220 --> 00:21:19.690
you want the diverse
perspectives.

00:21:19.690 --> 00:21:22.740
And I can't emphasize
this enough.

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:26.190
It's so important to have that
filter when you start a design

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:29.190
sprint, because it really
shapes the end deliverable.

00:21:29.190 --> 00:21:33.330
I've seen teams where
that kind of team synergy

00:21:33.330 --> 00:21:36.410
and that diversity has
led to true innovation,

00:21:36.410 --> 00:21:40.080
and I think authentic team
spirit, which really matters.

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:44.160
Because we want people returning
to these sprints and to do them

00:21:44.160 --> 00:21:48.250
as their active product
development practice.

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:51.810
So it's really important that
we make their time worthwhile

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:55.080
and that they feel that
they get a lot from it.

00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:57.240
JENNY GOVE: I'll
just add that I've

00:21:57.240 --> 00:22:00.360
had experience bringing in
different sorts of people

00:22:00.360 --> 00:22:02.910
in different roles at Google
into different sprints.

00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:06.480
So some success
stories I can remember

00:22:06.480 --> 00:22:10.262
were running a sprint for games,
around games, and around apps

00:22:10.262 --> 00:22:12.345
for games, when I brought
in business development,

00:22:12.345 --> 00:22:14.610
and they had such a different
perspective than we'd

00:22:14.610 --> 00:22:17.880
heard before, that we
hadn't involved before that.

00:22:17.880 --> 00:22:20.160
I've run sprints on
privacy and security.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:21.600
We definitely brought in legal.

00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:23.190
We brought in policy.

00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:26.760
We also at that time brought
in external academics

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:28.560
into our sprint teams.

00:22:28.560 --> 00:22:30.720
So sometimes thinking
even wider than the people

00:22:30.720 --> 00:22:34.020
in your company, where you can
do that is really important.

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:37.440
And like I said
before, teams that

00:22:37.440 --> 00:22:43.890
have the client perspective
often a lot better than we do.

00:22:43.890 --> 00:22:47.760
Definitely bringing in user
research, but also sales,

00:22:47.760 --> 00:22:50.940
developer relations,
different roles

00:22:50.940 --> 00:22:57.032
like that such a good
connection to the end users.

00:22:57.032 --> 00:22:57.740
KAI HALEY: Great.

00:22:57.740 --> 00:23:00.950
So have any of you
guys had any sprints

00:23:00.950 --> 00:23:05.330
that you considered to be
maybe a little bit of a failure

00:23:05.330 --> 00:23:06.470
or went off the rails?

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:08.299
And what did you
do to save them?

00:23:08.299 --> 00:23:09.590
SUMIER PHALAKE: I've had a few.

00:23:12.200 --> 00:23:14.660
So I ran a sprint recently.

00:23:14.660 --> 00:23:18.140
So I work in a group that makes
products for emerging markets,

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:19.790
and I was working
with a team that

00:23:19.790 --> 00:23:23.870
really wanted to be in this
one particular emerging market.

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:26.660
And I planned the
sprint perfectly,

00:23:26.660 --> 00:23:28.340
and everything was
going really well.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:31.310
And there were a bunch of
really great lightning talks

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:34.100
based on really strong
foundational research,

00:23:34.100 --> 00:23:38.060
and what we found out was none
of that research was actually

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:42.320
presenting a strong user
need or a user problem.

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:44.600
And so what ended
up happening was

00:23:44.600 --> 00:23:47.810
over the course of
that sprint, everyone

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:49.640
had a lot of great
ideas, but no one really

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:53.210
knew what a good idea was
because they didn't know

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:55.280
what they were solving for.

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:57.440
And so I've been
very guilty of this.

00:23:57.440 --> 00:23:59.450
Before the sprints runs,
I was just like, hey,

00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:01.610
throw your lightning
talks into the slide deck.

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:04.260
As long as the lightning
talks are done, I'm happy.

00:24:04.260 --> 00:24:06.009
And I'd rarely actually
go through them

00:24:06.009 --> 00:24:07.800
and try to synthesize
and try to understand

00:24:07.800 --> 00:24:10.640
if the inputs
actually make sense.

00:24:10.640 --> 00:24:14.090
And so my learning was if
your inputs aren't great,

00:24:14.090 --> 00:24:15.830
your outputs aren't
going to be great.

00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:19.370
So you have to make sure that
you use your inputs in a way

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:24.960
to guide the team to come
to really good solutions.

00:24:24.960 --> 00:24:29.150
The other situation I've
faced is just personalities.

00:24:29.150 --> 00:24:31.894
Sometimes you will have a really
loud, strong voice in the room.

00:24:31.894 --> 00:24:33.560
You've all been in
sprints where there's

00:24:33.560 --> 00:24:36.620
been a super senior executive
or someone super senior who

00:24:36.620 --> 00:24:39.290
is very opinionated, and
everyone else kind of

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:43.580
feels scared to oppose them or
come up with their own ideas.

00:24:43.580 --> 00:24:46.040
And this is where your
skills as a Sprint Master

00:24:46.040 --> 00:24:47.240
really come into play.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:53.826
You have to point to other
people and ask them to speak.

00:24:53.826 --> 00:24:55.200
You have to keep
reminding people

00:24:55.200 --> 00:24:56.960
that sprints are
very democratic.

00:24:56.960 --> 00:24:58.880
And if voting is not
working for you--

00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:01.460
because sometimes someone
will vote for an idea and then

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:03.790
everyone else will vote
for that same idea--

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:06.920
you should try doing the note
and vote method where people

00:25:06.920 --> 00:25:09.590
can write down their votes on a
piece of paper with no one else

00:25:09.590 --> 00:25:12.672
seeing, and then you
tally them up after.

00:25:12.672 --> 00:25:14.630
I've always had, there's
always this one person

00:25:14.630 --> 00:25:17.150
in the sprint who is
convinced that their idea is

00:25:17.150 --> 00:25:20.180
the right one, and
everyone else is wrong.

00:25:20.180 --> 00:25:23.810
And for that, what I've
found is really successful

00:25:23.810 --> 00:25:25.430
is you just give them the stage.

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:26.950
Because if you don't
let them speak,

00:25:26.950 --> 00:25:29.780
it's just going to keep
bubbling up for days.

00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:32.300
So just give them the
stage; let them speak.

00:25:32.300 --> 00:25:35.000
Again, remind everyone
that this is a democracy.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:37.310
And then after
they've had their say,

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:40.056
if still no one agrees,
then it's really

00:25:40.056 --> 00:25:41.930
like there's nothing
else they can do, right?

00:25:41.930 --> 00:25:44.910
So that's been really
effective for me.

00:25:44.910 --> 00:25:46.910
BURGAN SHEALY: I like to
say there are no failed

00:25:46.910 --> 00:25:51.260
sprints, because you always
learn something from a sprint.

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:53.330
That being said,
there's always a chance

00:25:53.330 --> 00:25:55.490
for your sprint to go
in a different direction

00:25:55.490 --> 00:25:56.750
than you planned.

00:25:56.750 --> 00:25:58.340
Sometimes that can
be a good thing,

00:25:58.340 --> 00:25:59.990
and sometimes it's
really important

00:25:59.990 --> 00:26:04.100
to bring the sprint team back to
the original sprint challenge.

00:26:04.100 --> 00:26:06.440
Occasionally I've
had teams that get

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:09.950
really excited and gravitate
towards solutions that

00:26:09.950 --> 00:26:12.740
are cool or shiny, but don't
really address the user

00:26:12.740 --> 00:26:14.700
problem in the best way.

00:26:14.700 --> 00:26:17.210
So that's when having a
pre-defined sprint challenge

00:26:17.210 --> 00:26:20.420
is really important, and
having your success metrics

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:23.530
and your design
principles defined,

00:26:23.530 --> 00:26:25.130
so that you can
refer back to them

00:26:25.130 --> 00:26:28.010
and make sure that you're really
addressing the problem that you

00:26:28.010 --> 00:26:30.080
set out to address.

00:26:30.080 --> 00:26:33.110
Another challenge I've
faced is keeping everyone

00:26:33.110 --> 00:26:34.980
engaged for the full sprint.

00:26:34.980 --> 00:26:36.860
It's a big chunk of time.

00:26:36.860 --> 00:26:40.080
I was in one sprint where
we had a key participant--

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:42.080
someone who was really
important to the sprint--

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:45.320
leave after only
two hours, after he

00:26:45.320 --> 00:26:47.810
discovered that we were pretty
serious about our laptops

00:26:47.810 --> 00:26:48.582
down policy.

00:26:48.582 --> 00:26:50.540
He said he could only
participate in the sprint

00:26:50.540 --> 00:26:53.390
if he could be on his
laptop the whole time.

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:56.540
So we actually decided to
do daily checkins with him,

00:26:56.540 --> 00:26:59.600
half hour checkins at the end
of each day, to get his feedback

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:02.300
and make sure that he knew
where the sprint was going,

00:27:02.300 --> 00:27:06.320
but that would not interrupt the
flow of all the other sprinters

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:07.460
with that distraction.

00:27:10.052 --> 00:27:11.510
JOSH LOVEJOY: Yeah,
