what I hear you guys saying.

00:29:57.920 --> 00:30:01.910
Outside of the standard
product development process,

00:30:01.910 --> 00:30:06.170
what are other use cases
that you've applied

00:30:06.170 --> 00:30:08.750
the sprint methodology to?

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:13.710
So I've done quite a few
sprints for nonprofits.

00:30:13.710 --> 00:30:16.052
And I know Burgan has, too.

00:30:16.052 --> 00:30:17.510
I've been very
passionately working

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:18.926
with nonprofits
for several years.

00:30:18.926 --> 00:30:20.593
And I used to do UX
workshops with them.

00:30:20.593 --> 00:30:22.592
And then after I learned
the sprint methodology,

00:30:22.592 --> 00:30:23.900
I started doing sprints.

00:30:23.900 --> 00:30:26.150
And that's actually
been really effective

00:30:26.150 --> 00:30:30.971
because nonprofits actually
have interesting challenges.

00:30:30.971 --> 00:30:32.720
Unfortunately, they
don't often have a lot

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:35.810
of budget for UX resources.

00:30:35.810 --> 00:30:38.380
And so things like
design thinking and stuff

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:40.130
like that, they just
don't have the luxury

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:42.170
to actually have the
right people to help

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:43.970
them think through that.

00:30:43.970 --> 00:30:46.250
But having said that,
they are actually

00:30:46.250 --> 00:30:49.280
super excited to
work with designers.

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:52.340
They face some of the same
organizational challenges

00:30:52.340 --> 00:30:55.601
that we face, like getting
stakeholder, buy-in, changing

00:30:55.601 --> 00:30:57.350
things that they've
done the same way that

00:30:57.350 --> 00:31:00.090
have tried and trusted
for many, many years.

00:31:00.090 --> 00:31:02.240
A lot of times, they're
stuck using legacy systems

00:31:02.240 --> 00:31:03.950
that they want to break out of.

00:31:03.950 --> 00:31:07.670
So it's been actually really
great working with them

00:31:07.670 --> 00:31:11.420
to kind of get a consensus
to change product direction.

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:14.324
Having said that,
I think if you're

00:31:14.324 --> 00:31:15.740
running a sprint
with a nonprofit,

00:31:15.740 --> 00:31:17.281
I think it's really,
really important

00:31:17.281 --> 00:31:20.510
to staff them with even more
UX designers as participants

00:31:20.510 --> 00:31:23.250
than you would otherwise.

00:31:23.250 --> 00:31:25.370
And that's because
in my experience,

00:31:25.370 --> 00:31:28.340
there's not a lot of knowledge
about things like user journeys

00:31:28.340 --> 00:31:30.500
or sketching or
flows or just some

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:33.681
of that terminology we
take for granted now.

00:31:33.681 --> 00:31:35.430
There isn't a lot of
experience with that.

00:31:35.430 --> 00:31:37.469
So it kind of need
more of a helping hand.

00:31:37.469 --> 00:31:39.260
And every time I've
actually had more UXers

00:31:39.260 --> 00:31:42.590
on the team, if you split
the team into groups,

00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:44.000
each group should have a UXer.

00:31:44.000 --> 00:31:47.460
It's worked out
really, really well.

00:31:47.460 --> 00:31:49.310
The other sprint I
recently ran was--

00:31:49.310 --> 00:31:52.670
I don't know if anyone's
read Jake Knapp's medium

00:31:52.670 --> 00:31:54.934
article about a brand sprint--

00:31:54.934 --> 00:31:56.600
the product that I'm
b working on Google

00:31:56.600 --> 00:31:58.850
is really ready
for a rebranding.

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:03.020
And so I spent three hours
with key stakeholders

00:32:03.020 --> 00:32:06.140
just defining the
personality of our product,

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:09.900
our vision for 20 years, who
we are, what our values are.

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:12.360
And that was a super
great for just getting

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:14.730
everyone aligned, getting
all these abstract notions

00:32:14.730 --> 00:32:16.230
of what our brand
is into something

00:32:16.230 --> 00:32:17.940
that was really concrete.

00:32:17.940 --> 00:32:21.780
So then we actually start
deploying that brand as a logo

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:23.640
or in marketing,
we have something

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:25.640
to point to and keep
ourselves honest

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:27.060
and make sure we're
not off-brand.

00:32:27.060 --> 00:32:30.090
so that was actually
really great.

00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:32.310
BURGAN SHEALY: Yeah, I've
run a number of sprints

00:32:32.310 --> 00:32:35.040
with nonprofits as well.

00:32:35.040 --> 00:32:39.060
Several for google.org, which
is Google's philanthropic arm

00:32:39.060 --> 00:32:39.670
as well.

00:32:39.670 --> 00:32:41.580
And I think one of
the key differences

00:32:41.580 --> 00:32:45.090
that I've enacted with
nonprofits, for instance,

00:32:45.090 --> 00:32:47.830
is having users in
the entire sprint.

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:52.260
So in one, the nonprofit
Project Concern International

00:32:52.260 --> 00:32:57.600
was using satellite data to
give and show pastoralists

00:32:57.600 --> 00:33:00.810
in sub-Saharan Africa
current vegetation

00:33:00.810 --> 00:33:04.170
so that they could understand
where good grazing land was.

00:33:04.170 --> 00:33:06.510
This was becoming a problem
due to climate change,

00:33:06.510 --> 00:33:09.280
and their grazing
lands were changing.

00:33:09.280 --> 00:33:11.400
So the program that
they had was hugely

00:33:11.400 --> 00:33:14.790
successful with a 50%
reduction in herd mortality

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:18.690
and 80% adoption by
local populations.

00:33:18.690 --> 00:33:22.110
However, the delivery system
was really ineffective.

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:26.130
They were printing out
maps, paper maps, and then

00:33:26.130 --> 00:33:29.280
hand delivering those
to the local population.

00:33:29.280 --> 00:33:33.970
So our challenge was to provide
these maps on a smartphone.

00:33:33.970 --> 00:33:37.020
So we had Google UXers,
we had PCI staff,

00:33:37.020 --> 00:33:40.440
we had a mapping specialist,
we had local developers.

00:33:40.440 --> 00:33:43.560
And then we had a number of
users in the sprint with us.

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:46.650
And having the users in
the sprint was critical.

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:49.800
They were able to work
with the developers

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:52.320
to really help the
developers understand

00:33:52.320 --> 00:33:54.630
the user needs from the
very outset of the project.

00:33:54.630 --> 00:33:58.020
The UXers were able to
understand the technology

00:33:58.020 --> 00:34:00.700
challenges and opportunities.

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:05.420
And just having the users as
code designers in the process

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:10.199
was really important so
that they owned the solution

00:34:10.199 --> 00:34:15.403
and actively worked with the
team to develop the solution.

